{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346978/1938011101/0128.xml":{"full_text":"P Spotlight Is Turned\nif On Water bury GOP\n(Continued from Page 1)\nGovernor Wilbur L. Cross, who cur\nr\u00abntly has ordered the investigation.\nPryor Forgot Something\nMr. Pryor, however, overlooked\nthe Republican makeup of the\nSenate which sanctioned Commis\nsioner Macdonald\u2019s re-appointments\nsince 1931, officials remarked today.\nAnd the fact that the highway de\npartment has been one of the most\nimportant fortresses of the Republi\ncans for many years was given as\nreason for publically expressed\namusement by the Democratic State\nCommittee Chairman J. Francis\nSmith, of Waterbury, over Mr.\nPryor\u2019s statements.\nLaughs at Pryor\nRepresentative Swayne, likewise,\nsaid that he laughed when I read\nMr. Pryor\u2019s statement. The Republi\ncan House leader is considered\nresponsible to a large extent for the\ncurrent investigation, the outcome\nof his fight with State Senator J.\nKenneth Bradley over financial\n\u201cdictatorship\" over the Fairfleld\nCounty Republicans Committee.\nThe latter has promised Mr. Swayne\nan accounting of the funds of the\nFairfield County organization which\nis said to be in process.\nPryor Close to Local G.O.P.\nThe grand jury, according to Mr.\nSwayne, should not fail to investi\ngate every aspect of the donations\nby the Fairfield Republicans for\nthe purpose of tracing all disposi\ntion of the Merritt parkway funds.\nHe said he is not familiar with Wa\nterbury election which saw a deal\nFairfield committee beyond knowl\nedge that National committeeman\nPryor is \u201cvery close\" to certain\nWaterbury Republicans and w-as a\n\u2018\u2018close observer\" of the recent Wa\nterbury lection which saw a deal\nbetween Republican Town Chair\nman J. Warren Upson\u2019s organiza\ntion and a group of insurgent Demo\ncrats. resulting in the joint nomi\nnation of Democratic Senator\nGeorge T. Culhane to oppose re\nelection of Mayor Frank Hayes.\nDemocratic lieutenant-governor and\ncurrently fifth-term mayor of Wa\nterbury.\nAppounra uy iciiipicmu\nRepresentative Swayne pointed to\nthe appointment of Commissioner\nMacdonald in 1923 by the Republi\ncan Governor Charles A. Temple\nton of Waterbury, saying that Wa\nterbary always \"seemed to have\na considerable place in the regard\nof the State Highway Department\nHe remarked, also, the part played\nby Senator Bradley, Committeeman\nPryor's closest ally, in seeking con\nfirmation of Commissioner Macdon\nald by the governor in 1935 when the\nRepublicans in the Senate formed a\ncoalition with Socialists to gain\ncontrol.\nMay Result In Expose\nAttorney General Charles S. Mc\nLaughlin is understood to plan that\nthe grand jury shall not confine\nIts investigation to the land deals\nand examination of checks and en\ndorsers already is under way in the\nWHY UDGA TABLETS CURB\nEXCESS ACID DISTRESS OF\nSTOMACH ULCERS\nIf your stomach painisaccompamed by GAS,\nheartburn, belching, bloating, burning, IN\nDIGESTION. nausea,etc..don'ttake baking\naoda.dangerousdrugsorhalf-way measures,\nbut follow the advice of the thousands of\nformer acid-stomach sufferers who recom\nmend UDG A Tablets to help neutralize ex\neats stomach acids UDGA Tablets,based on\na physician's successful prescription, work\nfast to bring relie f f rom excess acid stomach\ndistress. Week\u2019streatmentsupply only $1 on\niron-cl ad guarantee of results or money back!\nGet UDGA and relief or get your money back.\nRecommended by\nAPOTHECARIES HALL CO\u201e\nCARROLL CUT RATE,\nLIGGETT\u2019S\nand all good drug stores.\nFairfield County state\u2019s attorney\u2019s\noffice. This, It was Indicated, will\nresult in exposing the details of the\nFairfield County donation to the\nWaterbury campaign fund.\nBridgeport. Jan. 11\u2014(UP)\u2014State\u2019s\nAttorney Lorin W. Willis may apply\nto superior court either today or\ntomorrow for the summoning of an\nextraordinary grand jury to investi\ngate rights-of-way land sales for\nthe Merritt parkway and other\ntransactions of the state highway\ndepartment.\nWillis conferred with state police\nCommissioner Anthony Sunderland\nafter announcing appointment of\nAttorney Earle W. Smith as a spe\ncial assistant for the Inquiry.\nAttorney-General Charles J. Mc\nLaughlin, at the same time, an\nnounced at Hartford he would as\nsign an assistant to aid Willis. He\nmay choose assistant Attorney\nGeneral Richard J. Corkey.\nSunderland.\u2019s interview with Willis\nconcerned delegation of state po\nlice for investigatory activities in\nConnecticut with the grand jury\ni probe.\nThe Attorney General instructed\nstate and comptroller Charles C.\nSwartz and treasurer Guy B. Holt\ntoday to prepare photostatic copies\nof all deeds, checks and other in\nstruments in connection with the\nMerritt Parkway purchases.\nThere were approximately 400\ndeeds and as many checks, it was\nunderstood. They will be given the\ngrand jury when it convenes at\nBridgeport.\nHartford. Conn., Jan. 11\u2014(UP)\u2014\nSpecial Fairfield county assistant\nState's Attorney Earl W. Smith an\nnounced today he would establish\nheadquarters in the attorney gen\neral's office here-during the grand\njury investigation of Merritt park\nway and general highway depart\nment negotiations.\nSmith will act as agent between\nAttorney General Charles J. Mc\nLaughlin and State\u2019s Attorney Lorin\nW. Willis.\nIt was considered possible appli\ncation might be made late today for\nsummoning the grand jury. It must\nbe done on petition by Willis before\nSuperior Court Judge Carl Foster\nat Bridgeport.\nThe court will convene the jury\nif, in its opinion, there is sufficient\nreason presented by the state\u2019s at\ntorney for its inquiry.\nAL CAPONE MOST\nHATED OF ALL MEN\nSan Francisco, Jan. 11\u2014(UP)\u2014A1\nCapone remains the \u201c'most hated\"\nman on Alcatraz Islar^i, according\nto William M. Ritchey, who was\nheld in city jail here today after\nhis release from the prison.\nRitchey gained temporary freed\nom yesterday after he signed a\npauper\u2019s oath in lieu of a $5,000\nfederal fine. He was re-arrested at\nSan Francisco and was held for\ntransfer to Providence, R. I., where\nhe is wanted on a thieft charge. He\nsaid he would fight extradition.\nThe climate of Alcatraz is \u2018\u2019mis\nerable,\u201d he said, but the \"food is\ngood, the place is clean, the silence\nis deadly.\u201d\nRitchey was sentenced in Balti\nmore in 1933 for theft of $10,000\nworth of watches through a transfer\nof trunks aboard a train.\nThe sentence was five years in ad\ndition to the $5,000 fine.\nAs of January 1, 1937, there were\n43,400 automobile dealers in the\nUnited States.\nF. W. GRAND'\nLEADER IN REAL VALUES\nPURE FOOD MARKET\n1S1 SOUTH MAIN ST.\nDOWN GO MEAT PRICES!\nPURE PRINT\nLARD\nnm no civnri\nMINCED HAM\nVEAL LOAF\nAMERI. BOLOGNA\nHALF OR WHOLE\n2 lbs\n2.5*\nDAISY MAID\nBUTTER\n2 lbs\nLamb Chops 2 ibs 29c\nFRESH SLICED\nShoulder Steak lb\nSALT PORK ib\nCROC ERY\nSPECIALS\nL1UHI MtAl\nTUNA FISH\n2 Regular Size\nOCTAGON LAUNDRY\nSOAP\n6 ST 25c\nBALLOON WHITE\nSOAP FLAKES\nSt 31c\nJERSEY\nCORN FLAKES\nCAMBRIDGE BRAND\nSweet Pickle Relish\nIT 21c\nAUNT JEMIMA\nPANCAKE FLOUR\nST 10c\nFirst Photos: As War Rages\nAbout Key City Of Teruel\nBlankets, clothes, and meagTe food supplies burden the refuge families who hasten away from Teruel as the\nSpanish Loyalist and rebel armies spread death and destruction in their colossal battle for the key city on\nthe front near Valencia. Now the homes of most of these people likely are a shambles, for the resistance\nof the rebel garrison made the town a target for heavy shelling.\nBundled up against the near-zero cold that has taken almost as great a toll as have shot and shells, Indal\necio Prieto, center, minister of national defense for the Spanish Loyalist government, stands in a trench to\nwatch the battle at Teruel. In this first picture received from the Teruel battle the officer at right points\nout the operations of the Loyalist forces at the height of the combat.\nRepublicans Are To\nBlame Themselves\n(Continued from Page 1)\ngent search for \u201citems\" for political\ncapital, back through the year.\nMinor Answers Charge\nHarry W. Minor, president of the\npolice and fire boards, added his\ncomment today to the publication\nof a story concerning his receipt\nof a check for $900.\n\u201cEvery cent I have ever received\nfrom the city I\u2019ve given full value\nfor in services rendered,\" Commis\nsioner Minor said.\nJudge Thoms recalled that his\npart in the Republican-contrived\nmerit system petition proceedings,\neventually deemed illegal by Judge\nEdwin C. Dicnenson in the superior\ncourt, was considerable in the terms\nof time and service. He added that\nthe election recount took even more\nof his service and time during the\nlong process of inspection and check\ning of the 04 voting machines, to the\nresult that the election count of\nModerator James R. McMahon was\nconfirmed in preponderant detail.\nFormer Mayor Guilfoile\nFormer Mayor Francis P. Guil\nfoile. described as receiving $6,000,\nlikewise received payment for part\nin these court proceedings brought\nby the Republican organization, now\npaid by taxpayers, it was declared.\nSo, in the list of payments most re\ncently used as material for Repub\nlican attack on the administration\nfrom the controller\u2019s office \u201cfront,\u201d\nthe major portion of the amounts\ncited are, in the sense that officials\ndeem them so, the costs to the city\nof the political machinations of the\nRepublicans and Independent Dem\nocrats last summer and fall.\nUpson \u201cLays Another Egg\"\nWhich, an official told The Demo\ncrat, makes the picture of the at\ntack take on humor of the variety\nto warrant his comment: \u201cMr. Up\nson just laid another egg.\u201d\nHe questioned whether the tax\npayers will find the situation of the\nRepublicans criticizing payments\ntheir organization made necessary\nin the poltiical litigation a construc\ntive move in their first participa\ntion in city affars (the confroller\u2019s\noffice), in sixteen years.\nFinance Board to Meet\nWith a special meeting of the\nboard of finance called for 4 o\u2019clock\ntoday by Mayor Frank Hayes for\nconsideration of payroll items and\nother business of the controller\u2019s\noffice, further attack by Controller\nRowland is anticipated along the\nlines of his presently-publicized pro\ngram. The mayor has called the\nmeeting, too, it is understood, for\nconsideration of several opinions\nasked by the controller of Corpora\ntion Counsel Charles S. O\u2019Connor.\nOne of these opinions deals with\nthe controller\u2019s request for ruling on\nwhether trucking and personal serv\nices of workmen should be a joint\npayroll item, the bills separated.\nAnother opinion, sought by the con\ntroller and the commissioners, is on\nthe matter of whether the controller\nmay pay certain items within char\nter provision subject to, but before,\napproval of the majority of the\nboard.\nCity Bills Held Up\nOn Uie premise that his respon\nsibility for various December items\nSMITH\nfctt BROS. v\nCOUGH\nDROPS\nTRADE\nIARIC\nCONTAIN VTTAMSN A\n\non the warrant sheets wras involved,\nthe controller, at the first meeting\nwith the finance commissioners, re\nfused to sign the warrants. These\npayments of city accounts are held\nup and various creditors of the city\nare seeking their money due, it was\nreported.\nMeanwhile, the controller\u2019s office\nis involved in \u201cscrutiny\u201d of various\naccounts paid and (the making up of\nthe payroll, due tomorrow. The \u201cat\ntack\u201d will continue on these 'ac\ncounts at today\u2019s meeting, it is un\nderstood, although the controller\nwas not willing to confirm this as\nsumption.\nAttack Items Quoted\nAmong the \u201cattack\u201d items which\nhe is expected to bring before the\nboard are the following:\nFrancis P. Guilfoile, ex-mayor,\nlegal services, $6,000.\nNancy Delaney, work on the old\nage assistance rolls, $150.\nFrank Santalucia, truck hire and\nsendee, $5,511.50.\nAr thur Sullivan, use of auto, $40.\nDaniel F. Bowes, services, two\npayments of $40 each.\nAbrigador digger, Philip Coppeto,\npresident, use of equipment, $1,850.\nAlderman Shepatin, New Ha\nven, auditors, $975.\nThomas P. Kelly, traveling ex\npenses to Boston and New York in\nconnection with a \u201ccity of Water\nbury loan $187.\nThe Bridgeport Herald, advertis\ning, $132.\nDaniel Pickett, services to the tax\ncollector\u2019s office checking tax rec\nords, $151.\nA. Lambo, contractor, rentals of\nequipment and parts, $12,183.61.\nD. J. Donovan, of Meriden, for\nstone delivered to the street depart\nment, $1,437.09.\nrxancis r. reeiey, transporting\nvoting machines, $250.\nBernardine Lawlor, overtime serv\nices aiding the, Kingsley Co., audi\ntors, $32.\nMartin Sweeney and Prank Doyle,\novertime work, $42.50.\nJulia A. Laguna, overtime work,\n$53.\nFrancis C. O\u2019Donnell, work for\nthe registrars of voters and the\ncontroller\u2019s office, $90.\nHelen Tehan Smith, overtime, $48.\nWilliam J. Dunphy, 17 fountain\npen and pencil sets, $255.\nThe payment of $6,000 made to\nformer Mayor Guilfoile was for a\nbill itemized as follows:\n\"Revision of Waterbury city\ncharter, 1931 to 1937\u20141937 spe\ncial acts inclusive. Consultation\nand assistance on preparation of\ncase of state of Connecticut ex\nrel John M. Brodie et als vs.\nPeter Griffin et als, relative to\nthe adoption of the merit sys\ntem for the city of Waterbury\n\u2014Mandamus action consultation\nand assistance in relation to the\ncase of state of Connecticut ex\nrel George Culhane et al vs.\nJames McMahon et al re: can\nvass of election returns\u2014Man\ndamus action Legislative con\nsultation.\u2019\u2019.\nMOTHER OF PLAYGROUNDS\nLexington, Mass., Jan. 11 (U.P.)\n\u2014Services will be held tomorrow for\nMiss Ellen M. Tower, 89, \u201cthe\nmother of the American play\ngrounds,\u201d who died Sunday at her\nhome.\nA native of Lancaster, she with\nMrs. James T. Field and Mrs. Kate\nGannett Wells organized, supervised\nplaygrounds In 30 public schools in\n1885. She continued the work 23\nyears until school committMi as\nsumed supervision.\nWhite Canada plum blossoms turn\nwhen they fade.\nMAYOR HAYES IS\nSTARTING PROBE\n(Continued from Page 1)\nmayor\u2019s investigation and comment\nat noon today, said that he had \"no\nstatement\u201d. He is expected to ex\ntenuate his publicized \u201cattack\u201d or\naffairs of his office at the board oi\nfinance meeting at 4 o\u2019clock today.\nWelcomes Information\nIn tV; mayor's statement was thf\nexpression, \u201cto try to ascertair\nwhether the books are missing.\u2019\nFurther, the mayor said that h<\nwould welcome\u201d any informatior\nconcerning the whereabouts of th<\nbooks in question.\u201d\nInasmuch as the books are large\nheavy volumes, ponderous enougt\nto prove a fair load for any one in\nterested in removing them, ques\ntion whether they could have beer\ncarried from the office without thf\ncarrier being observed brought com\nment from various officials today\nAt one office, where important citj\nrecords are kept, it was admittec\nthat concern existed always for thf\nsafety of the material which is es\nsential to the city\u2019s affairs.\nBocks Moved About\nAnother official commented or\nthe fact that the books, said tc\ncontain stubs showing payments b.i\nthe city of accounts for all of 193'\nand eleven months of last year, liac\nbeen moved from one city office t<\nanother while the auditors frorr\nKingsley Co. were conducting\ntheir annual inspection of the city\u2019j\naccounts. This audit has been ir\nprogress for some time and will no\nbe completed until the first of nexi\n,month, whep the December ac\ncounts will be finished.\nGEO. STAEBLER\nIS EXONERATED\n(Continued from Page 1)\nceased was riding with her hus\nband, George A. Staebier wester\nly on the Cheshire Waterbury\nroad in a 1935 Dodge Sedan owned\nby Mr. Staebier. They were re\nturning to their home in Water\nbury after a visit to Mr. Staebler's\nbrother-in-law. George Staebier\nwas a properly licensed operator\nof motor vehicles. At a point about\n250 feet westerly from the East\nFarms school a car approached\nthe Staebier car whose lights were\nvery bright and interfered with\nStaebler's vision. It appeared to\nStaebier that this car was com\ning directly at him at a fast rate\nof speed. He turned to the right,\ngot completely oil the road and\nthe car struck a post on the north\nerly side of the road, badly dam\naging the right side of the car\nand injuring Mrs. Staebier. She\nwas removed to St. Mary\u2019s hospital\nin Waterbury where she died on\nthe 13th day of Decemzer, 1937, at\n7:50 a. m. There is no evidence\nthat Staebier was operating his\ncar either at an excessive rate of\nspeed or in such a manner as to\nconstitute criminal negligence.\nI find therefore that the death\nof the said Ella Staebier was due\nto a fracture of the right humerus,\nfracture of the nose, lacerations\nand body bruises and thrombo\nphlebitis which developed from\nsaid injury, but that said death\nwas not due to the criminal negli\ngence of the said George Staeb\nier.''\nTWO WERE KILLED\nSpringfield, Mass., Jan. 11 <U\nP.) Two persona were killed by t\nliit-nm motorist while crossing t\nstreet last night. The victims werf\nMrs. Faith M. Read, 50, and Herberl\nSwireo. 17.\nJAPAN NtAKlNli\nCRISIS IN CHINA\n(Continued from Page 1)\nleaflets Issued by what was called\nthe \"Kwangtung People\u2019s Represen\ntative association.\u201d Kwangtung prov\nince includes Canton. The leaflets\nurged adoption of a four point pro\ngram:\n1. \u2014Overthrow of Generalissimo\nChlang Kai-Shek, who, it was\ncharged, \u201cbrought humiliation and\nsuffering on the people.\u201d\n2. \u2014Overthrow of communism.\n3. \u2014Overthrow of the Kuomlntang,\nthe government political party,\nwhich it was charged accepted com\nmunism.\n4. \u2014Support of a \"new leader who\nwill protect the land, restore peace\nand work for the protection of\nKwangtung.\u201d\nWho the leader was, the leaflets\ndid not say.\nTokyo, Jan. 11\u2014(UP)\u2014Japan\u2019s\nleaders met today in a solemn im\nperial conference, fifth of its kind\nin the country\u2019s modem history, to\ndecide definitely on a long range\nprogram of action in China.\nNational interest centered on the\nconference in the belief that deci\nsions of paramount importance to\nJapan, China and the Far East im\npended. Emperor Hirohito, in the\nuniform of Generalissimo of the\narmies, presided. Cabinet ministers\nsat on either side or him, nearest\nthe throne. Then ame the highest\nofficers of the army and navy, the\narmy on the left, the navy on the\nright. Civilian personages were in\nterspersed among them.\nRoyalty Was There\nThree imperial princes attended\nthe gathering\u2014Fumimaro Konoye,\nPremier, Hotohito Kan-In, chief of\nGeneral staff of the army, and\nHiroyasu Fushimi, chief of General\nStaff of the navy.\nRumors swept through the capi\ntal as to the result of the meeting\nseverance of diplomatic relation*\nwith China; a formal declaration of\nwar; a drive on Canton; declaration\n6f a kingdom in north China; even\ndiscussion of peace terms with\nChina. But all were based on sur\nmise.\nuunuu 1 urn mg roini\nAll that seemed certain was that\na definite turning point had ben\nreached in a strange clash between\nthe two powers of the Par East\na clash in which tens of thousands\nof men had died in six months of\nfighting by hundreds of thousands\nof troops over thousands of miles\nof territory, while China and Japan\nstill maintained formal diplomatic\nrelations and. on the international\nrecords; ostensibly remained at\npeace. There were persistent reports\nthat the conference was called be\ncause, after weeks of effort by Ger\nmany, China had refused to submit\nto peace terms offered secretly by\nJapan. The alternative seemed to be\na fight to the finish, regardless of\ncost or consequence, a fight in\nwhich Japan feels she must\ntriumph.\nmoreTddedto\nWPA PAY ROLLS\n(Continued from Page 1)\nafter his conference vith Mr. Roose\nvelt that the 250.000 increase since\nDec. 1 was a minimum figure and\nthat it might be as high as 300.000\nI when the official returns are tabu\nlated.\nThe acting administrator ,who has\nbeen in charge of WPA since Harry\nHopkins went to the Mayo Clinics\nlast month, said that it is usually\neight or nine weeks from the time\nan individual loses his job until he\ngoes on the relief rolls. He said that\nconsiderably more pressure would be\nexerted on WPA by Feb. 1. WPA\neconomists have estimated that\nmore than 2,000,000 persons have\nbeen thrown out of work by the\ncurrent business recession, and that\nan additional million will be added\nto the jobless army by Feb. 1.\nCongress Appropriation\nThe treasury report revealed that\nsince May. 1935, Congress appro\npriated $8,422,078,685 for relief pur\nposes. This amounts to more than\n$65 per person in the country for\nall relief costs.\nThe report revealed that Presi\ndent Roosevelt was holding back\n$494,795,288 in unallocated funds\nfrcm the present fiscal year\u2019s appro\npriation of $1,500,000,000. This\nmoney, it was understood, can be\nshifted to V/PA or other relief\naoenns need develops.\nThe WPA still has slightly more\nthan one-third of its allocation for\nthe entire year. It has spent since\nJuly 1, 1S37, a total of $629,999,120\nand had $331,787,732 left as an un\nexpended balance.\nReach Peak Next Month\nOn Jan. 1, WPA rolls totaled 1,\n666,997. Relief officials expect rolls\nto reach a peak of ,900,000 in Feb\nruary' or early in March. It ap\npeared certain that WPA would\nhave to be given a major portion of\nthe unallocated money.\nDuring the entire life of the\n1935, 1936 and 1937 relief appropria\ntion bills, WPA received 49.4 cents\nout of every relief dollar allocated\nby the president. For the present\nfiscal year of which six months\nhave passed, the WPA received ap\nproximately two out of every three\ndollars allocated. Officials believe\nthat WPA may receive an even\nhigher percentage of these allo\ncated funds as relief rolls grow.\nBRITISH DOCTOR\nMET WITH DEATH\nJerusalem, Jan. 11\u2014(UP)\u2014British\npolice were ordered today to track\ndown the killers of Dr. J. L. Stark\ney, renowned archeologist who be\ncame the first British civilian killed\nin the outbreak of Jewish-Arab Ter\nrorism.\nThe 46-year-old Briton whose ex\ncavations in the near east contribut\ned many of the Rockefeller arch\neological museum\u2019s chief exhibits\nwas shot and killed yesterday by\nArab bandits while en route from\nHebron to Jerusalem. The attack oc\ncurred near his archaeological ex\ncavations at Beitjibrin.\nStarkey was motoring from Heb\nron accompanied by his Arab drivei\nand two servants when halted by the\nbandits. He was forced to leave his\ncar and turned wallet and revolver\nover to the Arabs.\nThe driver and the servants were\nhandcuffed while one of the ban\ndits fired his rifle six times at\nStarkey. The body was mutilated.\nGrieve, Bisset& Holland, fee.\n\u201cWaterbury\u2019* Dependable Store\u201d\nOUR STORE-WIDE\nJANUARY\nCLEARANCE SALE\nContinues to offer hundreds of items in stan\ndard up-to-date merchandise at very low\nClearance Prices.\nStorting Wednesday Morning We'll Have\nTwo Very Special Events\nGLOVE SALE\nHere is a Real Opportunity tc Stock Up In Gloves\nat a Big Reduction In Price!\nMaker\u2019s samples of genuine imported Kid Gloves\nand genuine Pigskin. \u201cPerrin Make\u201d. Gloves that were\nmade up as samples and have been shown in sample line.\nSlightly wrinkled from handling but have no imperfec\ntions. Slip-on and one clasp styles. Tailored and with\nnovelty stitching or fancy cuffs. Black, Brown, Beige\nand White. Regular price $2.98 to $3.98. C4 0*7\nSpecial Price.*..\nAN EXTRA SPECIAL VALUE IN\nWOMEN\u2019S SLIPS\nA nationally known make and quality that thousands\nof women in Waterbury have been satisfied with and\nask for by name. These have slight imperfections and\nfailed to pass the rigid inspection as perfect goods.\nThey will give absolute satisfaction in wear!\nCrepe, silk and satin. Tailored or trimmed with im\nported lace. Tea Rose and white. Regular QO\nprice $1.98. Special price.\nNow is the time to take advantage of the\nClearance Sale Prices on Sheets and\nPillow Cases\nIf you need them for the future It will pay you to\nstock up now at January Clearance prices.\nLET US TELL YOU ABOUT OUR EASY\nPAYMENT PLAN!\nf\nTen Died In Crash\nOfAirlinesTransport\n(Continued from Page\nbeyond the rugged, 10,000-foot peaks\nof Bridger Mountains, the eastbound\nplane struck nose first with an im\npact that drove the fuselage into the\nmotors and scat.cred its fragments\nin all directions.\nInstant Explosion\nInstantly, the big liner exploded.\nA wisp of smoke that rose from the\ncanyon attracted a farmer six miles\naway. Two woodchoppers who saw\nthe plane fall reached the scene\nahead of him. They sent word by\ntelephone from a deserted dude\nranchhouse half a mile away, that\nthe two pilots and eight passengers\nall probably had died mercifully the\nmoment the plane struck, and that\nthe bodies of all except veteran pilot\nNick B. Mamer had been trapped in\nthe fuselage and burned.\nPilot\u2019s Body Thrown Out\nMamer was thrown clear of the\ndebris. His clothing was afire when\nthe woodsmen arrived. They doused\nthe flames with snow but Mamer\nwas dead. The heat from the burn\ning plane was so intense that they\ncould not approach within 100 yards\nof it.\nThe scene was 15 miles northeast\nof Bczeman. The plane was bound\nfrom Seattle to Chicago, left Butte\nat 2:05 p. m. tMST) and was due in\nBillings at 3:47.\nThe woodsmen believed that\nMamer had tried to bring the plane\ndown in the level clearing because of\nthe storm\u2019s high wind, and that he\nwas unable to level it off for a land\ning.\nRoster of Dead\nPilot Mamer, of Seattle, one of\nthe most experienced flyers in the\nnorthwest, who, with Art Walker,\nmade the first non-stop, rouijd trip\nflight across the continent in'1928\u2014\na trip that required five days\u2014with\ntheir plane \u2018\u2018Sun God\u201d which they\nrefueled in the air\nFred W. West, Seattle, co-pilot.\nG. A. Anderson, Spokane.\nDouglas McKay, Winnipeg, Can\nada.\nL. Levin, Butte. Mont.\nI. E. Stevenson, Seattle.\nW. E. Borgenheimer, Bason, Mont.,\nemploye Of the airline.\nA. L. Croonquist, Billings, Mont.,\nstate traffic manager for the airlines.\nWalter Ton, St. Paul.\nTed Anderson, St. Paul, Northwest\nAirlines mechanic.\nOne a Newspaperman\nDouglas McKay, formerly was a\nprominent Canadian newspaperman\nand eidtor of The Beaver, house or\ngan of Hudson\u2019s Bay company. He\nhad been attending a company\nmeeting in Victoria, B. C., and left\nVancouver by air Sunday to return\nto his home in Winnipeg. He was\nauthor of a book, \u201cThe Honorable\nCompany.\nIt was the first time Northwest\nAirlines had lost a passenger in 11\nyears service, and it was the second\ndisaster to commercial aviation in\nthe western mountains this winter.\nNatives reported this morning that\na snowstorm, lashed by a wind ol\nnear gale proportions, was sweeping\nthe mountainous country. Removal\nof the bodies was delayed. Snow\nwas drifting over the wreckage, ob\nliterating the black spot 100 yards\nwide where the heat of the burning\nplane thawed the snow and exposed\nthe earth.\nSupervise Removal\nSheriff Lovitt Westlake and Coro\nner Howard Nelson went out from\nBozeman to supervise the removal of\n1 bodies to a sled provided by forest\nrangers. The sheriff 's office was in\ni formed that the plane's gas tanks\nI had exploded. After the charred\nruins'had cooled, the searchers\nlooked into the fuselage and saw the\ni bodies of two men, both of them\ni headless. Jack Bartlett, a Bozeman\nbusiness man who went out to the\ncanyon and returned late last night,\nsaid that the plane had come from\nI the west across the Bridger range\nj where there is a cliff with a sheer\ndrop of 1,000 feet which causes a\nterrific downdraft. He said the plane\nprobably dropped 300 or 400 feet in\nstantly in this draft. The Yellow\nstone National Park lies directly\nsouth of here, and the wreck oc\ncurred nearly on a line between the\nI park and the Canadian border.\nWood Choppers Saw It\nC. A. Larson and Glenn Whit*\nwere out in the forest, between the\nGallatin and Shields River valleys,\nchopping wood when they saw the\nplane fall. They were only a few\nhundred yards away, but could not\nsee the plane hit the ground because\nof the trees. They dropped their\naxes and ran to the property of Alex\nSwanson, where the wreckage lay.\nAfter rescuing the body of the pilot,\n'there was nothing more they could\ndo until the lire subsided.\nThe men satisfied themselves that\nall/ the plane's occupants must be\ndead and telephoned the news to\nBozeman. Forest rangers went out\nwith a sled to carry away the bodies.\nSome of the men thought the\nplane was burning when it struck\nthe ground. Others disputed this, as\ndid company officials in St. Paul,\nwho said the fire probably started\nafter the gas tanks burst In striking.\nFIVE LEADERS OF\nINDUSTRY MEET\n(Continued from Page 1)\nHouse lent special significance to\nthe gathering.\nEarly said the conferees would\nengage In a general discussion of\nthe business situation.\nIt was believed, in the light of\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s recent utter\nances, that sales problems would be\ndiscussed. He has emphasized desir\nability of spreading orders over the\nyear in order to stabilize business\ninstead of lumping them and thus\ncreating rush periods at one time\nand dull periods the next.\nSet Late Today\nMr. Roosevelt will sit down with\nthe business leaders immediately\nafter he finishes his press confer\nence.\nThe White House meeting with\nthe industrial leaders heading a\ngroup of the largest business enter\nprises in the country\u2014follows by\nthree days the president\u2019s appeal In\nhis Jackson Day Dinner address for\nbusiness and Industry to cooperate\nwith the government in meeting\nthe business recession.\nIt was expected that Mr. Roose\nvelt would seek from the indus\ntrialists their views on causes of the\nrecession and cooperative means for\nhalting the economic slump.","height":"28336","width":"20824"}}
